data.title: Merit Medical Systems: Strong Financial Performance and Strategic Growth Drive Buy Rating
data.description:
Michael Matson has given his Buy rating due to a combination of factors including Merit Medical Systems’ impressive financial performance and strategic initiatives. The company reported record-high gross margins and exceeded expectations for both revenue and earnings per share in the third quarter of 2025. Additionally, the management’s decision to raise revenue and EPS guidance for 2025 reflects confidence in the company’s future performance.
Another contributing factor is the company’s organic revenue growth, which improved to 7.8% year-over-year in the third quarter of 2025, compared to 6.7% in the previous quarter. The increase in both gross and operating margins, along with a significant rise in free cash flow from $38 million in the third quarter of 2024 to $53 million in the same period of 2025, further supports the positive outlook. Matson also notes the potential for additional revenue from the WRAPSODY product, pending a decision on a Medicare outpatient transitional pass-through add-on payment, which could enhance the company’s financial standing starting in 2026.

data.title: PBF Energy: Persisting Free Cash Flow Challenges and Turnaround Strains Justify Sell Rating
data.description:
Jason Gabelman has given his Sell rating due to a combination of factors impacting PBF Energy’s financial performance and outlook. Despite the company’s recent outperformance on earnings and the reaffirmation of the Martinez restart timeline, PBF Energy has struggled to generate positive free cash flow for six consecutive quarters. This trend is expected to persist into the future, even with anticipated mid-cycle crack spreads and improved differentials in 2026.
Additionally, while the company has received substantial insurance proceeds and asset sale inflows, these have not been sufficient to offset the negative free cash flow situation. The upcoming year is expected to be a heavy turnaround period, which could further strain financial resources and impact throughput expectations. These elements, combined with the company’s current valuation based on projected EBITDA, underpin Gabelman’s decision to maintain a Sell rating, albeit with an increased price target of $25.
